<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>howler</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2002<br />
	Location: currently being evaluated
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>On sullon as a hunter playing for the good team, I devoted at least 3 hours of my day to hunting the low level evils and neuts.  It kept the server clean of bluebies.  Quite frankly, if you're going to play on sullon or rallos, you better have thick skin.  If you're hoping to reach level 10 on your one night off, you better expect to be ganked by 2 level 65 shadowknights looking for some late night fun.  Your nights will be ruined regularly, your server will be full of drama, you'll constantly be looking over your shoulder for 60 levels, and life in EQ as you knew it before will never be the same.<br />
<br />
And I say this in the nicest way possible because it was the most rewarding 2 years of my EQ life.  If you thought killing a PoP god for the first time was an accomplishment on Bluebie Ro, try doing it when you have 66% of the server trying to train you.  They don't want you in their backyard and if you think you're going to just walk in, you've got another thing coming.<br />
<br />
It's kill or be killed because I just kicked you in the face and took your epic mob, you know, the one you've been camping all night.  You have two options, grab your corpse and get out of my zone or bring a possy.  You just better hope yours is bigger than mine.<br />
<br />
That's pvp and it's the greatest thing EQ ever had to offer.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><font color="black"><b><font size="2">Erny</font>, Iksar Defiler [Nocturnal Souls]</b></font><br />
<a href="http://rivals.eq2guilds.org" target="_blank">Crushbone</a></div>
	
	
