<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>howler</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2002<br />
	Location: currently being evaluated
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Truthfully, while slaughtering the lower levels did let out a lot of anger (and you'll be frustrated a bit if you play long enough), it's true intent was to bring out the higher levels.  Once you start griefing a zone like the Overthere or the Field of bone (FoB was my favorite), those low levels instantly call in their friends.  You call in your friends, and bam, before you know it, you have a brawl.  You know there's a good time going on when you're running through PoK and 20 people are sitting at the FoB or OT portals, licking their wounds.<br />
<br />
Though I don't harbor the whole blue bashing sentiments, you'll find that that mentality really doesn't exist in most people on zek servers.  Like with most things, there are a vocal minority who might say things like this on forums.  Though I think it's mostly to get a rise out of people.  Though you might tend to be a "bit" more aggressive when you play on a zek, I think the current zek players on this forum have shown repeatedly their good character.<br />
<br />
And though it is extremely frustrating, like somebody mentioned, it can also be the most rewarding.  The servers are a bit different, like vigdis mentioned.  Hard coded teams on Sullon meant that there were definite sides.  I've read lately that many people's idea of a fun mmorpg has faction as a major part of it.  On SZ, If you see a troll or an ogre, you either run or you get your buddies together and teach him to stay out of gfay.  There is no question what his intent is, he's there to kill you.  That's faction in its truest form.  So while I might have spent 2 or 3 hours everday griefing FoB and the OT, I also spent a lot of time in Gfay, MM, and PoI protecting our sides' lower levels.  Like I said, most griefing is done to bring out the higher levels on each side.  Protecting your team's arse, and doing it well is extremely rewarding.  <br />
<br />
If you're a good and you're running through Gfay with your guild tag up, everybody in the zone knows that you represent the best of what the good team has to offer.  An evil's in the zone, expect a flood of tells with information on that creep.  You're a hero and if that's not addicting, I don't know what is.  On a zek, you can be Mr. Nasty or you can be that person that's always there to protect the backs of everybody around you.  Yeah, EQ is a roleplaying game, but on a zek, how you play and what type of character you create is much more pronounced in my mind.  Controlling the lives and deaths of so many people really brings out what your character is about.<br />
<br />
If you just want to check out what pvp is like, I strongly suggest you join Rallos.  You'll get a better feel for what a more balanced version of player combat is like.  Just don't lose your gear, remember to bag it all before you're ganked.  Get a group of your friends together and make a band of gnome magicians.  Once you hit level 8, go to gfay and run amuck.  Just because it's not lvl 65 pvp, it's still a riot.  If you've never experienced the end game and want to, don't join Sullon.  And don't join Sullon if you're not willing to put in your time for the first 50 levels.  In fact, I wouldn't recommend sullon until you know for sure that you love pvp.  Because while you may love it, you're about to hate it with just as much intensity.</p>
	
	
	
